default 
defaultSpecial Olympi
defaultcs believe that every person with an intellectual disability and their family should be provided with the information and support to understand what they need to do in order to optimize their health. In order for this to be achieved information, resources,
default systems and policies must exist at an individual, community and national level to support individuals and their families to realise healthy and productive lives. 
defaultIn Africa, over 27,000 free health screenings have been provided by Special Olympics between
default 2007-2013. This has allowed basic access to health care for 
defaultover 18,500 Special Olympics athletes 
defaultin 33 countries
default.
defaultThe results of these screenings illustrate
defaults
default the value of this care and highlight the striking disparity of access to healthcare for people w
defaultith 
defaulti
defaultntellectual disability living in the developing world compared to their global counterparts.
default&#xa0;
default For example, in Africa 
default72.5% of athletes screened by Special Olympics to date had never had an eye exam
